(42, 9, 19, 43, 1, 21, 21, 'Elias', 'Connection of Prophetic Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the question of prophetic identity, specifically regarding Elijah. In Luke, the people speculate about Jesus being Elijah, while in John, the inquiry directly addresses John the Baptist''s identity as Elijah.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 19, 43, 7, 40, 40, 'one of the old prophets is risen again', 'Recognition of Prophetic Identity', 'This connection highlights the people''s recognition of Jesus as a prophet. In both passages, there is a discussion about Jesus'' identity, with references to prophets like John the Baptist and the old prophets.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 20, 40, 16, 15, 17, 'But whom say ye that I am?', 'Peter''s Confession of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s declaration of Jesus as the Christ. The connection is strengthened by the similar phrasing of the question posed by Jesus, inviting recognition of his identity.', 'parallel', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 20, 43, 1, 49, 49, 'The Christ of God', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus'' divine identity. Peter identifies Jesus as ''the Christ of God,'' while Nathanael acknowledges Him as ''the Son of God.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 20, 43, 4, 29, 29, 'The Christ of God', 'Recognition of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Jesus as ''the Christ.'' Peter acknowledges Him as ''the Christ of God,'' while the Samaritan woman refers to Him as ''this the Christ.'' This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus'' messianic role.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 20, 41, 8, 29, 29, 'whom say ye that I am', 'Peter''s Confession of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s declaration of Jesus as the Christ. The phrasing in both verses shows a direct parallel in Peter''s response to Jesus'' question about his identity.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 20, 44, 9, 22, 22, 'The Christ of God', 'Recognition of Christ''s Identity', 'This connection highlights the acknowledgment of Jesus as the Christ. In both passages, the identity of Christ is central, with Peter declaring Him as ''The Christ of God'' and Saul proving ''this is very Christ.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 20, 44, 17, 3, 3, 'The Christ of God', 'Identity of Christ Connection', 'This connection highlights the identification of Jesus as ''the Christ.'' Both passages affirm Jesus'' messianic identity, with Peter declaring Him as ''The Christ of God'' and Paul preaching that Jesus is ''Christ.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 20, 40, 5, 47, 47, 'The Christ of God', 'Connection of Identity and Action', 'This connection highlights the theme of identity and how it influences behavior. In Luke, Peter identifies Jesus as ''The Christ of God,'' while Matthew emphasizes the expectation of behavior among those who recognize their identity, suggesting that true followers should act differently than others.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 21, 40, 16, 20, 20, NULL, 'Disciples'' Silence Command', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' command to his disciples to remain silent about his identity as the Christ. This connection highlights a shared theme of secrecy regarding Jesus'' messianic role.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 21, 40, 17, 9, 9, 'Tell no man', 'Jesus'' Command to Silence', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' instruction to keep certain revelations secret. In Luke, he commands them not to tell anyone, while in Matthew, he specifies to tell the vision to no man until after his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 21, 41, 8, 30, 31, NULL, 'Messianic Secret Theme', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' command to keep his identity secret. This connection highlights the theme of the ''Messianic Secret'' in the Gospels, where Jesus instructs his followers not to reveal who he is.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 22, 23, 53, 1, 12, 'rejected of the elders and chief priests', 'Suffering and Rejection of the Messiah', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering and rejection of the Messiah. Luke 9:22 mentions the Son of man being rejected and slain, while Isaiah 53 describes him as ''despised and rejected of men'' and ''wounded for our transgressions.''', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 22, 42, 24, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection of Suffering and Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of the Son of man suffering and being raised on the third day. They highlight the themes of rejection, crucifixion, and resurrection, linking Jesus'' fate in a cohesive narrative.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 22, 42, 18, 31, 34, 'and be slain, and be raised the third day', 'Prophetic Suffering of the Son', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of the Son of man''s suffering and death, as well as his resurrection on the third day. The specific details of rejection, mockery, and death in Luke 18:31-34 echo the earlier prediction in Luke 9:22.', 'prophecy', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 22, 41, 9, 31, 31, NULL, 'Connection of Suffering and Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering and death of the Son of man, followed by his resurrection on the third day. This connection highlights the shared theme of Jesus'' impending sacrifice and triumph over death.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 22, 41, 10, 33, 34, 'and be slain, and be raised the third day', 'Connection of Suffering and Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering and rejection of the Son of man, culminating in his death and resurrection on the third day. They share similar themes regarding the fate that awaits Jesus in Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 22, 44, 4, 25, 28, 'rejected of the elders and chief priests', 'Connection of Suffering and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering and rejection of Jesus. Luke 9:22 speaks of Jesus being rejected and slain, while Acts 4:25-28 recounts the rulers gathering against Him, fulfilling this prophecy.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 22, 60, 1, 11, 11, 'suffer many things', 'Connection of Suffering and Glory', 'Both passages emphasize the sufferings of Christ and the subsequent glory. Luke 9:22 speaks of the necessity of suffering, while 1 Peter 1:11 refers to the Spirit of Christ testifying about these sufferings and the glory that follows.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 23, 40, 10, 38, 39, 'take up his cross', 'Connection of Discipleship and Sacrifice', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of taking up one''s cross as a symbol of commitment to following Jesus. They highlight the theme of self-denial and the paradox of losing one''s life to gain true life in Him.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 23, 42, 14, 26, 27, 'take up his cross', 'Discipleship and Self-Denial', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of self-denial and bearing one''s cross as essential to discipleship. The call to ''take up his cross'' in Luke 9:23 parallels the requirement to ''bear his cross'' in Luke 14:27, highlighting the commitment required to follow Jesus.', 'theme', 0.9649999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 23, 45, 8, 13, 13, 'deny himself', 'Self-Denial and Mortification', 'This connection highlights the theme of self-denial in both passages. Luke 9:23 emphasizes ''deny himself,'' while Romans 8:13 discusses ''mortify the deeds of the body,'' both calling for a rejection of fleshly desires.', 'theme', 0.8879999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 23, 41, 8, 34, 38, 'take up his cross', 'Call to Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of self-denial and taking up one''s cross to follow Jesus. They highlight the cost of discipleship and the importance of prioritizing spiritual over worldly gains.', 'theme', 0.8109999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 23, 43, 12, 25, 26, 'follow me', 'Self-Denial and Following Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of self-denial and following Jesus. Luke 9:23 speaks of taking up one''s cross, while John 12:26 encourages serving and following Him.', 'theme', 0.804, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 23, 51, 3, 5, 5, 'deny himself', 'Self-Denial and Mortification', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of self-denial and the active rejection of sinful behaviors. In Luke, the call to ''deny himself'' parallels the instruction in Colossians to ''mortify'' earthly members, highlighting a theme of daily commitment to spiritual discipline.', 'theme', 0.671, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 23, 56, 2, 12, 12, 'deny himself', 'Self-Denial and Righteous Living', 'This connection highlights the theme of self-denial in both passages. Luke 9:23 emphasizes denying oneself, while Titus 2:12 speaks of denying ungodliness, suggesting a parallel in the call to reject worldly desires.', 'theme', 0.671, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 24, 42, 17, 33, 33, NULL, 'Life and Loss Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the paradox of losing one''s life to find true preservation. The similar phrasing highlights a consistent theme of sacrifice for a greater purpose.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
